# 1. Feature Selection

## Definition

Selecting only the most useful features.

Not every feature contributes to learning.

Some may be irrelevant.

---

## Example

Movie Dataset

Available Features:

* Movie Name
* Genre
* Rating
* Popularity
* Vote Count

Selected Features:

* Rating
* Popularity

Reason:

Numerical features suitable for K-Means clustering.

---

# Benefits

* Faster training
* Reduced complexity
* Better performance

---

# 2. Feature Creation

## Definition

Creating new features from existing features.

---

## Example

Date of Birth

↓

Age

A model usually learns better from Age than Date of Birth.

---

## Example

Salary and Expenses

↓

Savings

Savings = Salary − Expenses

---

# 3. Feature Transformation

## Definition

Changing feature format without changing information.

---

## Example

Gender

Male

Female

↓

0

1

---

This process is called Encoding.

---

# 4. One-Hot Encoding

## Definition

Converts categorical variables into binary columns.

---

## Example

Color

Red

Blue

Green

↓

Red | Blue | Green

1 | 0 | 0

0 | 1 | 0

0 | 0 | 1

---

# Example

Future Improvement Planned

Movie Recommendation Project

Genre

↓

One-Hot Encoding

↓

Improved Recommendations

---

# 5. Feature Scaling

## Definition

Making features comparable in magnitude.

---

## Example

Age = 25

Income = 100000

Without scaling:

Income dominates.

With scaling:

Both contribute fairly.

---

## Methods

### Normalization

Range:

0 to 1

---

### Standardization

Mean = 0

Standard Deviation = 1

---

# Example

Customer Segmentation Project

Used:

StandardScaler

Reason:

K-Means performs better on scaled data.

---

# 6. Dimensionality Reduction

## Definition

Reducing the number of features while preserving information.

---

## Example

100 Features

↓

20 Features

↓

Faster Training

---

Common Technique:

PCA (Principal Component Analysis)

